{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775849381787,"sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","part":{"id":"prt_d78df1f97001CGtyku1hENhwrI","messageID":"msg_d78df11b2001q6vy1jRN0z2rIF","sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775849384582,"sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","part":{"id":"prt_d78df25fd001oO0bAbt4Bd5Pkx","messageID":"msg_d78df11b2001q6vy1jRN0z2rIF","sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_186c781569c34ff9a1aa0bce","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing JWT authentication and token issuance in `pkg/router`.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-011\n10: - **Module**: `pkg/router`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: M\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Background\n17: \n18: The router module requires JWT-based authentication to secure API endpoints and enable token-based access control. This includes both JWT validation for incoming requests and token issuance for authenticated clients.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Requirement: JWT Configuration\n23: \n24: ### Scenario: Router creates JWT handler with default configuration\n25: \n26: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with `jwtEnabled: true` and no explicit JWT configuration\n27: **WHEN** the router initializes\n28: **THEN** it SHOULD use default values: secret from environment or config, algorithm \"HS256\", expiry \"1h\"\n29: \n30: ### Scenario: Router creates JWT handler with custom configuration\n31: \n32: **GIVEN** a Router instance with JWT configuration: `jwtAlgorithm: \"RS256\"`, `jwtExpiry: \"24h\"`, `jwtIssuer: \"agentcube\"`\n33: **WHEN** the router initializes\n34: **THEN** it SHOULD configure RS256 algorithm, 24 hour expiry, and issuer to \"agentcube\"\n35: \n36: ### Scenario: Router disables JWT authentication\n37: \n38: **GIVEN** a Router instance with `jwtEnabled: false` (default)\n39: **WHEN** HTTP requests are received\n40: **THEN** the router SHOULD NOT validate JWT tokens\n41: **AND** no JWT middleware SHOULD be applied\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## Requirement: JWT Token Validation\n46: \n47: ### Scenario: Router validates valid JWT token\n48: \n49: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and configured secret\n50: **WHEN** a request arrives with a valid JWT token in Authorization header \"Bearer <valid-token>\"\n51: **THEN** the router SHOULD validate the token successfully\n52: **AND** extract the claims into the request context\n53: \n54: ### Scenario: Router rejects expired JWT token\n55: \n56: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled\n57: **WHEN** a request arrives with an expired JWT token\n58: **THEN** the router SHOULD reject the request\n59: **AND** return 401 Unauthorized with appropriate error message\n60: \n61: ### Scenario: Router rejects invalid signature JWT token\n62: \n63: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled\n64: **WHEN** a request arrives with a JWT token that has invalid signature\n65: **THEN** the router SHOULD reject the request\n66: **AND** return 401 Unauthorized with \"invalid signature\" error\n67: \n68: ### Scenario: Router rejects malformed JWT token\n69: \n70: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled\n71: **WHEN** a request arrives with a malformed JWT token (not 3 parts)\n72: **THEN** the router SHOULD reject the request\n73: **AND** return 400 Bad Request with \"malformed token\" error\n74: \n75: ### Scenario: Router extracts claims from valid JWT\n76: \n77: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled\n78: **WHEN** a request arrives with valid JWT containing claims: `sub`, `exp`, `roles`\n79: **THEN** the claims SHOULD be available in request context\n80: **AND** can be accessed by downstream handlers\n81: \n82: ---\n83: \n84: ## Requirement: JWT Token Issuance\n85: \n86: ### Scenario: Router issues JWT token for valid credentials\n87: \n88: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and `/login` endpoint configured\n89: **WHEN** a POST request arrives with valid username and password\n90: **THEN** the router SHOULD authenticate the credentials\n91: **AND** issue a JWT token with user claims\n92: **AND** return the token in the response\n93: \n94: ### Scenario: Router issues JWT with configured expiry\n95: \n96: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and `jwtExpiry: \"2h\"`\n97: **WHEN** a user logs in successfully\n98: **THEN** the issued token SHOULD have `exp` claim set to current time + 2 hours\n99: \n100: ### Scenario: Router issues JWT with configured issuer\n101: \n102: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and `jwtIssuer: \"agentcube\"`\n103: **WHEN** a user logs in successfully\n104: **THEN** the issued token SHOULD have `iss` claim set to \"agentcube\"\n105: \n106: ### Scenario: Router rejects invalid credentials\n107: \n108: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and `/login` endpoint\n109: **WHEN** a POST request arrives with invalid username or password\n110: **THEN** the router SHOULD return 401 Unauthorized\n111: **AND** NOT issue a JWT token\n112: \n113: ---\n114: \n115: ## Requirement: JWT Middleware\n116: \n117: ### Scenario: JWT middleware extracts token from Authorization header\n118: \n119: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT middleware enabled\n120: **WHEN** a request arrives with header `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n121: **THEN** the middleware SHOULD extract the token\n122: **AND** validate it\n123: \n124: ### Scenario: JWT middleware extracts token from query parameter\n125: \n126: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT middleware configured to allow query param\n127: **WHEN** a request arrives with query param `?token=<token>`\n128: **THEN** the middleware SHOULD extract the token from query\n129: **AND** validate it\n130: \n131: ### Scenario: JWT middleware allows public endpoints\n132: \n133: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT middleware enabled\n134: **WHEN** a request arrives at a public endpoint (e.g., `/health`, `/login`)\n135: **THEN** the middleware SHOULD skip JWT validation\n136: **AND** allow the request through\n137: \n138: ### Scenario: JWT middleware blocks unauthorized access\n139: \n140: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT middleware enabled\n141: **WHEN** a request arrives at a protected endpoint without token\n142: **THEN** the middleware SHOULD return 401 Unauthorized\n143: \n144: ---\n145: \n146: ## Requirement: JWT Claims\n147: \n148: ### Scenario: Router includes user ID in JWT claims\n149: \n150: **GIVEN** a user logs in successfully\n151: **WHEN** JWT token is issued\n152: **THEN** the token SHOULD include `sub` claim with user identifier\n153: \n154: ### Scenario: Router includes roles in JWT claims\n155: \n156: **GIVEN** a user with roles \"admin\", \"user\" logs in\n157: **WHEN** JWT token is issued\n158: **THEN** the token SHOULD include `roles` claim with array [\"admin\", \"user\"]\n159: \n160: ### Scenario: Router includes custom claims in JWT\n161: \n162: **GIVEN** a Router configured with custom claims (e.g., `tenant_id`)\n163: **WHEN** JWT token is issued\n164: **THEN** the token SHOULD include the custom claims\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ## Requirement: Token Refresh\n169: \n170: ### Scenario: Router supports token refresh endpoint\n171: \n172: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT enabled and refresh endpoint configured\n173: **WHEN** a valid (non-expired) JWT is sent to refresh endpoint\n174: **THEN** a new JWT token SHOULD be issued\n175: **AND** the new token SHOULD have fresh expiry time\n176: \n177: ### Scenario: Router rejects refresh with expired token\n178: \n179: **GIVEN** a Router with JWT refresh enabled\n180: **WHEN** an expired JWT is sent to refresh endpoint\n181: **THEN** the router SHOULD return 401 Unauthorized\n182: \n183: ---\n184: \n185: ## Requirement: Key Management\n186: \n187: ### Scenario: Router loads JWT secret from configuration\n188: \n189: **GIVEN** a Router with `jwtSecret: \"my-secret-key\"` configured\n190: **WHEN** JWT validation or issuance occurs\n191: **THEN** the router SHOULD use \"my-secret-key\" for signing/verification\n192: \n193: ### Scenario: Router supports RS256 with private key\n194: \n195: **GIVEN** a Router with `jwtAlgorithm: \"RS256\"` and private key configured\n196: **WHEN** JWT token is issued\n197: **THEN** the token SHOULD be signed with RS256 using the private key\n198: \n199: ### Scenario: Router validates RS256 token with public key\n200: \n201: **GIVEN** a Router with `jwtAlgorithm: \"RS256\"` and public key configured\n202: **WHEN** a request arrives with RS256-signed JWT\n203: **THEN** the router SHOULD validate using the public key\n204: \n205: ---\n206: \n207: ## Acceptance Criteria\n208: \n209: - [ ] JWT tokens are validated on protected endpoints\n210: - [ ] Expired tokens are rejected with 401\n211: - [ ] Invalid signatures are rejected with 401\n212: - [ ] Valid tokens expose claims in request context\n213: - [ ] Login endpoint issues JWT tokens\n214: - [ ] Token expiry is configurable\n215: - [ ] Token issuer is configurable\n216: - [ ] JWT algorithm is configurable (HS256, RS256)\n217: - [ ] Public endpoints bypass JWT validation\n218: - [ ] Token refresh endpoint works correctly\n219: - [ ] Custom claims can be included in tokens\n220: - [ ] Invalid credentials are rejected\n221: \n222: ---\n223: \n224: ## References\n225: \n226: - Delta Spec: `changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md`\n227: - Proposal: `proposal.md`\n\n(End of file - total 227 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing JWT authentication and token issuance in `pkg/router`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-011\n- **Module**: `pkg/router`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe router module requires JWT-based authentication to secure API endpoints and enable token-based access control. This includes both JWT validation for incoming requests and token issuance for authenticated clients.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775849384563,"end":1775849384579}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775849384609,"sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","part":{"id":"prt_d78df2a850012EdGQ7XCdPjioa","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d78df11b2001q6vy1jRN0z2rIF","sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":25035,"input":6688,"output":150,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":18197}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775849387423,"sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","part":{"id":"prt_d78df359c001X54doxWPo638Wf","messageID":"msg_d78df2ab90018BCZZKiHSqb64r","sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775849391043,"sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","part":{"id":"prt_d78df3df7001YO41RBYB1AcOir","messageID":"msg_d78df2ab90018BCZZKiHSqb64r","sessionID":"ses_287215b25ffe7CZXXnfStOQX5W","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_d97b1f99acc343a191338dea","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication and token issuance capabilities in `pkg/router` to replace the current static bearer token authentication. This enables stateless authentication, token expiration, claims-based authorization, and integration with external identity providers.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: The AR-010 router currently implements simple bearer token authentication where a static token is compared directly:\n12: \n13: ```go\n14: if parts[1] != a.token {\n15:     http.Error(w, \"Unauthorized\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n16:     return\n17: }\n18: ```\n19: \n20: This approach has significant limitations:\n21: - **No token expiration**: Tokens remain valid indefinitely\n22: - **No cryptographically secure verification**: Simple string comparison\n23: - **No claims-based authorization**: Cannot extract user info or permissions\n24: - **No token revocation**: Cannot invalidate active tokens\n25: - **No token refresh**: Clients must re-authenticate with credentials\n26: - **No standard compliance**: Not compatible with OAuth2/OIDC flows\n27: \n28: ### Goal\n29: \n30: Implement JWT-based authentication that:\n31: - Validates JWT tokens using cryptographic signatures (HMAC or RSA)\n32: - Supports token expiration and refresh\n33: - Extracts claims for authorization decisions\n34: - Provides token issuance endpoint for client authentication\n35: - Integrates with session management (AR-010) for seamless flow\n36: - Supports multiple signing algorithms (HS256, RS256)\n37: - Enables claims-based access control\n38: \n39: ### Value\n40: - Stateless authentication at scale\n41: - Standard-compliant authentication (RFC 7519)\n42: - Fine-grained authorization via claims\n43: - Reduced database load (no session lookup)\n44: - Support for external identity providers\n45: - Improved security with short-lived tokens\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## Scope\n50: \n51: ### In-Scope\n52: \n53: | Deliverable | Description |\n54: |-------------|-------------|\n55: | JWT Validator | Validate JWT signatures, expiration, issuer, audience |\n56: | Token Claims | Extract and store user ID, roles, permissions from claims |\n57: | Token Issuer | Issue JWT tokens on successful authentication |\n58: | Token Refresh | Refresh expired tokens with valid refresh tokens |\n59: | Middleware Integration | Replace existing auth middleware with JWT validation |\n60: | Configuration | JWT secret, algorithms, expiration, issuer settings |\n61: | Metrics | Track token issuance, validation failures, expiration events |\n62: \n63: ### Code Structure\n64: \n65: ```\n66: pkg/router/\n67: ├── jwt/\n68: │   ├── validator.go          # JWT validation logic\n69: │   ├── claims.go             # Custom claims struct\n70: │   ├── issuer.go             # Token issuance\n71: │   ├── keys.go               # Key management\n72: │   └── config.go             # JWT configuration\n73: ├── auth.go                   # Update to use JWT (existing)\n74: └── (existing files...)\n75: ```\n76: \n77: ### Configuration\n78: \n79: The router supports these new JWT configuration options:\n80: \n81: | Option | Type | Default | Description |\n82: |--------|------|---------|-------------|\n83: | JWTEnabled | bool | false | Enable JWT authentication |\n84: | JWTSecretKey | string | \"\" | Secret key for HS256 signing |\n85: | JWTPublicKeyFile | string | \"\" | Public key file for RS256 |\n86: | JWTPrivateKeyFile | string | \"\" | Private key file for RS256 |\n87: | JWTAlgorithm | string | \"HS256 | Signing algorithm (HS256, RS256, ES256) |\n88: | JWTIssuer | string | \"agentcube\" | Token issuer claim |\n89: | JWTAudience | []string | [] | Expected audience claims |\n90: | JWTAccessTokenTTL | duration | 15m | Access token time-to-live |\n91: | JWTRefreshTokenTTL | duration | 24h | Refresh token time-to-live |\n92: | JWTIssuerEndpoint | string | \"/auth/token\" | Token issuance endpoint |\n93: | JWTValidateOnStart | bool | true | Validate keys on startup |\n94: \n95: ### Out-of-Scope\n96: - OIDC provider integration — future enhancement\n97: - Distributed JWT validation (shared keys) — future enhancement\n98: - Token blacklisting/revocation list — future enhancement\n99: - Multi-tenant JWT claims — future enhancement\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## Impact Analysis\n104: \n105: ### Dependencies\n106: \n107: | Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n108: |------------|--------|---------|\n109: | github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5 | ^5.2 | JWT parsing and validation |\n110: | github.com/google/uuid | ^1.6 | Token ID generation |\n111: | github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/router | local | Existing router module |\n112: \n113: ### Upstream Dependencies\n114: \n115: - **AR-010 Session Management** — JWT tokens integrate with session store\n116: - **AR-009 Router Core** — Provides the reverse proxy foundation\n117: \n118: ### Downstream Consumers\n119: \n120: 1. **External Clients** — Obtain and use JWT tokens for API access\n121: 2. **Backend Services** — Validate JWT claims from router\n122: 3. **Monitoring Systems** — JWT metrics for security auditing\n123: \n124: ### Risks\n125: \n126: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n127: |------|----------|------------|\n128: | Key leakage | High | Use secure key storage, rotate regularly |\n129: | Algorithm confusion | High | Explicitly specify allowed algorithms |\n130: | Token forgery | High | Verify signatures with trusted keys |\n131: | Clock skew | Medium | Use leeway for expiration checks |\n132: | Large claims | Medium | Limit claim size, validate upfront |\n133: \n134: ---\n135: \n136: ## Alternatives Considered\n137: \n138: ### Option 1: JWT with Symmetric Keys (HS256) (Selected)\n139: \n140: **Approach**: Use a shared secret key for signing and validating JWT tokens.\n141: \n142: **Pros**:\n143: - Simple implementation\n144: - Low computational overhead\n145: - Easy key rotation\n146: - No external dependencies\n147: \n148: **Cons**:\n149: - Key must be shared between all instances\n150: - Key distribution challenge in multi-instance deployments\n151: \n152: **Decision**: Selected — provides the best balance of simplicity and security for initial implementation.\n153: \n154: ---\n155: \n156: ### Option 2: JWT with Asymmetric Keys (RS256)\n157: \n158: **Approach**: Use RSA key pair for signing (private key) and validation (public key).\n159: \n160: **Pros**:\n161: - Private key never leaves the issuer\n162: - Public key can be distributed freely\n163: - Better for distributed systems\n164: \n165: **Cons**:\n166: - More complex key management\n167: - Higher computational overhead\n168: - Larger token size\n169: \n170: **Decision**: Supported as configuration option for production deployments requiring key separation.\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ### Option 3: OAuth2/OIDC Integration\n175: \n176: **Approach**: Delegate authentication to external OAuth2 provider.\n177: \n178: **Pros**:\n179: - Industry standard\n180: - Social login support\n181: - Built-in MFA\n182: - Centralized user management\n183: \n184: **Cons**:\n185: - External dependency on identity provider\n186: - Network latency for validation\n187: - Complex setup\n188: - Not suitable for all deployments\n189: \n190: **Decision**: Deferred — valuable for enterprise deployments but adds significant complexity.\n191: \n192: ---\n193: \n194: ### Option 4: PASETO (Platform-Agnostic Security Tokens)\n195: \n196: **Approach**: Use PASETO instead of JWT.\n197: \n198: **Pros**:\n199: - Simplified security model\n200: - Explicit version header\n201: - No algorithm confusion attacks\n202: \n203: **Cons**:\n204: - Less ecosystem support\n205: - Fewer client libraries\n206: - Newer standard\n207: \n208: **Decision**: Rejected — JWT has broader ecosystem support and sufficient security for current use cases.\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ## Implementation Plan\n213: \n214: ### Phase 1: JWT Core\n215: - [ ] Define JWT configuration struct\n216: - [ ] Implement key loading (secret file, RSA key files)\n217: - [ ] Create Claims struct with standard + custom claims\n218: - [ ] Implement JWT validator with signature verification\n219: - [ ] Add expiration and claims validation\n220: \n221: ### Phase 2: Token Issuance\n222: - [ ] Implement token issuer with access/refresh tokens\n223: - [ ] Add token endpoint handler (/auth/token)\n224: - [ ] Support username/password authentication\n225: - [ ] Implement token refresh endpoint\n226: - [ ] Add token revocation (optional)\n227: \n228: ### Phase 3: Middleware Integration\n229: - [ ] Update Authenticator to use JWT validator\n230: - [ ] Extract claims and store in request context\n231: - [ ] Add claims-based authorization middleware\n232: - [ ] Support Authorization: Bearer <token> format\n233: \n234: ### Phase 4: Session Integration\n235: - [ ] Link JWT claims with session management (AR-010)\n236: - [ ] Store user ID from JWT in session\n237: - [ ] Enable session creation on JWT validation\n238: - [ ] Handle token refresh with session update\n239: \n240: ### Phase 5: Metrics and Observability\n241: - [ ] Track JWT validation attempts (success/failure)\n242: - [ ] Track token issuance counts\n243: - [ ] Track token expiration events\n244: - [ ] Add JWT-specific error logging\n245: \n246: ### Phase 6: Testing\n247: - [ ] Unit tests for JWT validation\n248: - [ ] Unit tests for token issuance\n249: - [ ] Unit tests for middleware\n250: - [ ] Integration tests with various algorithms\n251: - [ ] Key rotation tests\n252: \n253: ---\n254: \n255: ## Acceptance Criteria\n256: \n257: - [ ] JWT tokens are validated using configured algorithm\n258: - [ ] Expired tokens are rejected with 401 status\n259: - [ ] Invalid signatures are rejected with 401 status\n260: - [ ] Token endpoint issues access and refresh tokens\n261: - [ ] Refresh endpoint issues new access tokens\n262: - [ ] Claims are extracted and available in request context\n263: - [ ] JWT middleware integrates with existing auth infrastructure\n264: - [ ] Configuration supports both HS256 and RS256\n265: - [ ] JWT metrics are exported (jwt_validated_total, jwt_issued_total, jwt_validation_errors_total)\n266: - [ ] Unit tests pass with >70% coverage\n267: - [ ] Graceful handling of key rotation\n\n(End of file - total 267 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication and token issuance capabilities in `pkg/router` to replace the current static bearer token authentication. This enables stateless authentication, token expiration, claims-based authorization, and integration with external identity providers.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-010 router currently implements simple bearer token authentication where a static token is compared directly:\n\n```go\nif parts[1] != a.token {\n    http.Error(w, \"Unauthorized\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n    return\n}\n```\n\nThis approach has significant limitations:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775849391031,"end":1775849391040}}}}
